{"cursor":"12677","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"\n\nThe 'Luddites' were 19th-century English textile artisans who violently\nprotested against the machinery introduced during the Industrial Revolution that\nmade it possible to replace them with less-skilled, low-wage labourers, leaving\nthem without work. Historian Eric Hobsbawm has called their machine wrecking\n\"collective bargaining by riot\", which had been a tactic used in Britain since\nthe Restoration, as the scattering of manufactories throughout the country made\nlarge-scale strikes impractical. [http://libcom.org/history/machine-breakers-eric-\nhobsbawm Hobsbawm, Eric, 'The Machine Breakers', Past and Present 1 (1952), 57-\n70.] Autor, Frank; Levy, David and Murnane,\nRichard J. [http://econ-www.mit.edu/files/569 \"The Skill Content of Recent\nTechnological Change: An Empirical Exploration\"] Quarterly Journal of Economics\n(2003)\n\nAlthough the origin of the name 'Luddite' is uncertain, a popular theory is that\nthe movement was named after Ned Ludd, allegedly a youth who had smashed two\nstocking frames 30 years earlier, and whose name had become emblematic of\nmachine\ndestroyers. [http://www.leicesteruk.net/historydetail.php?id=13322&f= Anstey\nat Welcome to Leicester (visitoruk.com)] According to this source, \"A half-\nwitted Anstey lad, Ned Ludlam or Ned Ludd, gave his name to the Luddites, who in\nthe 1800s followed his earlier example by smashing machinery in protest against\nthe Industrial Revolution.\" Palmer, Roy, 1998, The Sound\nof History: Songs and Social Comment, Oxford University Press, ISBN 978-0-19-215890-\n1, p. 103 Chambers, Robert (2004), Book of Days: A\nMiscellany of Popular Antiquities in Connection with the Calendar, Part 1,\nKessinger, ISBN 978-0-7661-8338-4, p. 357 The name evolved into the\nimaginary General Ludd or King Ludd, a figure who, like Robin Hood, was reputed\nto live in Sherwood Forest. |title=The National Archives Learning Curve\n| Power, Politics and Protest | the Luddites}}\n","linknr":369,"url":"Luddite","recorded":1364048124,"links":["/w/index.php?title=Luddite&action=edit","/w/index.php?title=Luddite&action=edit","//en.wikipedia.org/apple-touch-icon.png","//bits.wikimedia.org/favicon/wikipedia.ico","/w/opensearch_desc.php","//en.wikipedia.org/w/api.php?action=rsd","//creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/3.0/","/w/index.php?title=Special:RecentChanges&feed=atom","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=ext.gadget.DRN-wizard%2CReferenceTooltips%2Ccharinsert%2Cteahouse%7Cext.wikihiero%7Cmediawiki.legacy.commonPrint%2Cshared%7Cmw.PopUpMediaTransform%7Cskins.vector&only=styles&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=site&only=styles&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=startup&only=scripts&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/geoiplookup","//meta.wikimedia.org","#mw-head","#p-search","/wiki/File:Luddite.jpg","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/7/73/Luddite.jpg/170px-Luddite.jpg","/wiki/File:Luddite.jpg","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf11/skins/common/images/magnify-clip.png","/wiki/England","/wiki/Industrial_Revolution","/wiki/Eric_Hobsbawm","/wiki/Collective_bargaining","/wiki/Restoration_(England)","#cite_note-1","#cite_note-econ-www.mit.edu-2","/wiki/Ned_Ludd","#cite_note-3","#cite_note-Palmer-4","#cite_note-Chambers-5","/wiki/Robin_Hood","/wiki/Sherwood_Forest","#cite_note-6","#Background","#Formation_of_movement","#Government_response","#In_retrospect","#In_contemporary_thought","#See_also","#References","#Further_reading","#External_links","/w/index.php?title=Luddite&action=edit&section=1","/wiki/Nottingham","/wiki/Handloom","/wiki/Wool","/wiki/Cotton","/wiki/Mill_(factory)","/wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_needed","/w/index.php?title=Luddite&action=edit&section=2","/wiki/Nottinghamshire","/wiki/West_Riding_of_Yorkshire","/wiki/Lancashire","/wiki/Middle